### Overview of JavaScript
JavaScript is a high-level, interpreted, programming language used to make web pages more interactive. It is a very powerful client-side scripting language that makes your webpage more lively and interactive.

![](https://d1jnx9ba8s6j9r.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/web-development-406x300.png)

It is a programming language that helps you to implement a complex and beautiful design on web pages. If you want your web page to look alive and do a lot more than just gawk at you, JavaScript is a must.

### Features of JavaScript:

![](https://d1jnx9ba8s6j9r.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/05/features-of-javascript-768x362.png)

- It is a Scripting Language and has nothing to do with Java. Initially, It was named Mocha, then changed to LiveScript and finally it was named JavaScript.
- JavaScript is an object-based programming language that supports polymorphism, encapsulation, and inheritance as well.
- You can run JavaScript not only in the browser but also on the server and any device which has a JavaScript Engine.

#####   Some of the Basics and Fundamentals discussed in the previous JavaScript Tutorial are:

- Variables
- Constants
- Data Types
- Objects
- Arrays
- Functions
- Conditional Statements
- Loops
- Switch case

###### In this advanced JavaScript Tutorial, we will get into the depth of advanced aspects of JavaScript.

### Recursion

Recursion is a programming pattern that helps in situations where a task can be naturally split into several tasks of the same kind, but simpler. Or when a task can be simplified into an easy action and a simpler variant of the same task.

![](https://d1jnx9ba8s6j9r.cloudfront.net/blog/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/recursion-343x300.png)

In the process of solving a task, a function can call many other functions. A partial case of this is when a function calls itself. Thus, it is known as recursion.

#### Example:

`function pow(x, n) {
if (n == 1) {
return x;
} else {
return x * pow(x, n - 1);
}
}

alert( pow(2, 4) ); // 16`

